From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Jun 2026 11:54:35 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] kati: run \$(shell ...) in the make's logical working dir,
 not process cwd
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

A sub-make reached in-process (make -C sub, or `cd sub && make`) never chdir's
the process — kati tracks a LOGICAL working_dir and uses it for include/glob/
stat. But run_command (\$(shell ...), regen) ran in the PROCESS cwd, so a
sub-make's `$(shell cat rel.txt)` looked in the parent dir and failed
("no such file"), yielding empty values.

Thread the Evaluator's working_dir into the shell path: shell_func_impl and
run_command take a `cwd`, used for BOTH the in-process runner (via the recipe
runner's cwd) AND the fork fallback (cmd.current_dir). \$(shell) now runs where
the makefile lives. eval.rs `!=` assignment and regen pass their working dir too.

Verified: a sub-make `VAL := $(shell cat val.txt)` now reads sub/val.txt
(VAL=[FROMSUB]) under both `make -C a` and `cd a && make`; previously empty
with "cat: val.txt: No such file". make + recursive real_build regressions pass.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01XyA6FzC6QGgsrjEYEBJV46
